Here is a simple example of a smart contract in Solidity, implementing a basic token using the ERC-20 standard:

```
pragma solidity ^0.8.0;

import "@openzeppelin/contracts/token/ERC20/ERC20.sol";

contract BasicToken is ERC20 {
    constructor(uint256 initialSupply) ERC20("BasicToken", "BTOK") {
        _mint(msg.sender, initialSupply);
    }
}
```

In this example, the `BasicToken` smart contract inherits from the `ERC20` contract provided by the OpenZeppelin library, which is a widely used and audited implementation of the ERC-20 token standard. The basic token has a name "BasicToken" and a symbol "BTOK". The constructor takes an initial supply as an argument and mints that amount of tokens to the address that deploys the smart contract.
